-- AI Customer Service Automation Track: 5 modules × 5 lessons = 25 lessons
-- All modules go under the 'money' path since these are income skills
-- AI Content Creation modules are orders 26-30, this track starts at order 31

-- ============================================================
-- TRACK: AI Customer Service Automation (modules 31-35)
-- ============================================================

insert into public.modules (path_id, title, description, "order")
select p.id, m.title, m.description, m.ord
from public.paths p
cross join (values
  ('Chatbot Foundations', 'Understand why every Filipino business needs automated customer service and learn the platforms, conversation design, and performance metrics that make chatbots work.', 31),
  ('Building with Tidio and ManyChat', 'Go deep into the two most popular chatbot platforms for Philippine businesses — ManyChat for Messenger and Tidio for websites — and build production-ready bots.', 32),
  ('AI-Powered Smart Support', 'Integrate Claude and GPT into customer service workflows to handle complex queries, train AI on business knowledge, and deliver multilingual support in English, Filipino, and Bisaya.', 33),
  ('Analytics and Optimization', 'Master customer service metrics, find bottlenecks in support flows, run A/B tests on chatbot responses, and build monthly reports that prove your value to clients.', 34),
  ('Selling Automation Services', 'Package your chatbot and automation skills into premium services, find clients, onboard them professionally, and build a recurring revenue business targeting 100K pesos per month.', 35)
) as m(title, description, ord)
where p.pillar = 'money';


-- ============================================================
-- MODULE 1 LESSONS: Chatbot Foundations
-- ============================================================

-- Lesson 1
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Why Every PH Business Needs a Chatbot',
  'The Philippines is the text messaging and chat capital of the world. Filipinos sent over 400 million Messenger conversations per day in 2025, making Facebook Messenger the de facto customer service channel for Philippine businesses. A 2025 Meta Philippines report revealed that 76% of Filipino consumers have messaged a business on Facebook before making a purchase. Yet 83% of Filipino small businesses still respond to customer messages manually — meaning a sole proprietor or small team is juggling order inquiries, product questions, delivery tracking, and complaints between all their other responsibilities. The result: slow response times, lost sales, and frustrated customers. According to a 2025 Zendesk study localized for Southeast Asia, 62% of Filipino consumers will abandon a purchase if they do not receive a response within 30 minutes. Most small businesses take 3-8 hours to respond. That gap is costing them thousands of pesos in lost revenue every single day. This is where you come in. A chatbot — an automated conversation system that responds to customer messages instantly, 24 hours a day, 7 days a week — solves this problem completely. A well-built chatbot handles the most common customer inquiries (product availability, pricing, store hours, order status, payment methods) in under 3 seconds. It qualifies leads, captures contact information, and routes complex questions to a human agent. It works while the business owner sleeps, during holidays, and during peak hours when message volume spikes. The ROI is dramatic: businesses that implement chatbots report a 35% increase in response rate, 25% reduction in customer complaints, and 15-20% increase in conversion rates. For an e-commerce store doing ₱200,000/month in revenue, a 15% conversion increase means ₱30,000 in additional monthly sales — far more than the cost of building and maintaining the chatbot. The Philippine chatbot market is still early. While large corporations (Globe, Jollibee, BDO) have sophisticated chatbot systems, the vast majority of SMEs — restaurants, salons, clinics, online shops, service providers — have zero automation. You are entering a market with massive demand and minimal competition at the SME level. Your target clients: any Filipino business with a Facebook page and more than 10 customer messages per day.',
  'Research and document the opportunity: (1) Visit 10 Facebook pages of local businesses in your area — restaurants, salons, shops, clinics. (2) Send each one a simple inquiry via Messenger: "Hi, what are your store hours?" or "Do you have [product] available?" (3) Record the response time for each business in a spreadsheet. Note: how long did it take? Was the response helpful? Did it feel automated or manual? (4) Calculate: if these businesses lose even 5 potential customers per day due to slow responses, and each customer is worth ₱500, that is ₱2,500/day or ₱75,000/month in lost revenue. Write this insight down — it is your sales pitch. (5) Research chatbot platforms: visit manychat.com, tidio.com, and chatfuel.com. Note the free tier limitations and pricing for each.',
  'How did it feel to experience slow business responses as a customer? Which businesses responded fastest, and did you notice any that seemed to use automation? How does understanding this customer pain point change how you see the business opportunity?',
  1
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Chatbot Foundations';

-- Lesson 2
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Chatbot Platforms Overview',
  'Choosing the right chatbot platform determines your efficiency, your client results, and your profitability. The Philippine market has specific needs — heavy Messenger usage, Shopee and Lazada integration, multilingual support (English, Filipino, Bisaya), and budget sensitivity. Here is an honest breakdown of the four major platforms. ManyChat is the king of Facebook Messenger automation in the Philippines, with over 1 million businesses globally using it. Free tier: up to 1,000 contacts with basic automation features. Pro: $15/month (approximately ₱870) for unlimited contacts and advanced features. Strengths: deep Messenger and Instagram DM integration, visual flow builder that requires zero coding, keyword triggers (customer types "price" and gets instant response), growth tools (comment-to-DM automation on Facebook posts — hugely effective for Filipino audiences), and e-commerce features (product catalogs, abandoned cart recovery). Weakness: primarily social media focused, limited website chat. Learn this first if your clients are Facebook-heavy businesses. Tidio is the best option for website-based chat, used by over 300,000 businesses. Free tier: 50 unique conversations per month. Paid: from $29/month (approximately ₱1,680). Strengths: clean website chat widget that installs in minutes on Shopify, WordPress, or any website, AI-powered responses that learn from your FAQ content, visitor tracking (see who is on the website and what they are looking at in real-time), and Shopee integration via Tidio API. Weakness: Messenger integration is less native than ManyChat. Learn this if your clients have websites or Shopify stores. Chatfuel is similar to ManyChat but with better AI integration capabilities. Free tier: 50 conversations per month. Pro: from $14.99/month. Strengths: no-code AI bot builder with GPT integration built in, strong Messenger and Instagram support, good for complex conversational flows. Weakness: smaller community and fewer tutorials than ManyChat. Dialogflow by Google is the enterprise-grade option for advanced AI chatbots. Free tier: generous — 1,000 text interactions per day. Strengths: most powerful natural language understanding, connects to any platform via API, supports Filipino and Cebuano languages natively, integrates with Google ecosystem (Sheets, Calendar, Maps). Weakness: requires basic technical knowledge (not purely no-code), steeper learning curve. Learn this when you are ready for complex, multi-platform bots. The recommended learning path for Filipino chatbot builders: start with ManyChat (1-2 weeks to master), add Tidio (1 week), then explore Dialogflow when you want to offer premium AI-powered bots. Specializing in ManyChat alone can earn you ₱15,000-₱40,000 per client project. Adding AI-powered bots via Dialogflow pushes your per-project pricing to ₱30,000-₱80,000.',
  'Get hands-on with the top platforms: (1) Create a free ManyChat account at manychat.com — connect it to your personal Facebook Page or create a test page. Spend 30 minutes exploring the dashboard, flow builder, and automation features. (2) Create a free Tidio account at tidio.com — install the chat widget on a free test website (use Carrd or Google Sites). Explore the AI response features and visitor tracking. (3) Visit Dialogflow (dialogflow.cloud.google.com) and create a free agent — explore the intent and entity system. Note how it handles natural language. (4) Compare all three platforms in a spreadsheet: ease of use (1-10), features relevant to PH businesses, free tier limitations, pricing, and your personal comfort level. (5) Decide which platform to master first based on your target client type (Facebook-heavy businesses = ManyChat, website-based businesses = Tidio).',
  'Which platform felt most intuitive to you, and why? How does the pricing of these tools compare to the value you could deliver to clients? If you could only learn one platform deeply, which would you choose and what types of Filipino businesses would you target?',
  2
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Chatbot Foundations';

-- Lesson 3
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Designing Conversation Flows',
  'A chatbot is only as good as its conversation design. A poorly designed bot frustrates users and drives them away — a well-designed one feels helpful, natural, and efficient. According to a 2025 Drift report, chatbots with well-structured conversation flows achieve 73% customer satisfaction rates, while poorly designed ones score below 30%. The difference is not technology — it is design thinking. The conversation flow design process: Step 1 — Map the user journey. Before touching any chatbot platform, map every possible reason a customer might message the business. For a typical Filipino restaurant: menu inquiry, reservation, delivery order, operating hours, location and directions, complaint, compliment, and job inquiry. For an e-commerce store: product availability, pricing, size or color options, order status, return or exchange, payment methods, and delivery timeline. These become your primary conversation paths. Step 2 — Build decision trees. Each primary path branches into sub-paths. "Menu inquiry" leads to: dine-in menu, delivery menu, or catering menu. "Order status" leads to: provide order number, then check status, then display result. Sketch these trees on paper or use a free tool like Miro before building in your chatbot platform. Visualizing the flow prevents dead ends and circular paths. Step 3 — Write responses in the right tone. Filipino customer service culture is warm, personal, and respectful. Your chatbot should reflect this. Use "po" and "opo" in Filipino responses. Address customers as "Ma'am" or "Sir" (standard in Philippine customer service). Keep responses under 3 sentences — long chatbot messages feel overwhelming, especially on mobile where 98% of Filipino Messenger users are reading. Add emoji sparingly but naturally — Filipinos use them heavily in chat. Avoid robotic language: instead of "Your query has been received," write "Got it! Let me check that for you." Step 4 — Design fallback responses. When the chatbot does not understand a message (and this will happen — Filipino customers use Taglish, abbreviations like "pls," "tnx," "mgkno," and regional languages), it needs a graceful fallback. Good fallback: "Sorry, I did not quite catch that! You can ask me about: 1) Our menu 2) Reservations 3) Delivery 4) Or I can connect you with our team." This redirects without making the customer feel stupid. Step 5 — Plan the human handoff. Not every conversation should stay automated. Complex complaints, custom orders, and emotional customers need a real person. Design clear triggers for human handoff: keywords like "manager," "complaint," "refund," or "frustrated," and include a smooth transition: "Let me connect you with [Name] from our team who can help you with this right away. They typically respond within 10 minutes."',
  'Design a complete conversation flow: (1) Choose a business type — restaurant, online shop, salon, or clinic. (2) List every reason a customer might message this business (aim for at least 8 scenarios). (3) Draw a decision tree for the top 3 scenarios — include every branch, sub-branch, and possible dead end. Use paper, Miro (miro.com, free), or Google Slides. (4) Write the actual chatbot responses for each branch — in Taglish, using the tone guidelines above. Aim for 3 sentences maximum per response. (5) Design your fallback response and at least 2 human handoff triggers. Save this complete flow design — you will build it in a platform in the next lesson.',
  'How did designing conversation flows change your perspective on how customers interact with businesses? What was the most challenging scenario to design for, and why? Did you find yourself thinking about edge cases that might frustrate a real customer?',
  3
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Chatbot Foundations';

-- Lesson 4
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Your First Chatbot in 2 Hours',
  'Theory is valuable but execution is what earns money. In this lesson, you will build a complete, functional chatbot from scratch using ManyChat — deployed on a real Facebook Page and ready to handle customer conversations. According to ManyChat internal data, their average user builds their first working bot in 90 minutes. With the conversation flow you designed in the previous lesson, you have a head start. Step-by-step build process: Minute 0-15: Setup. Log into ManyChat, connect your Facebook Page, and familiarize yourself with the Flow Builder. The interface is visual — you drag and drop conversation blocks, connect them with arrows, and add conditions and triggers. No coding whatsoever. Minute 15-45: Build your welcome flow. This is the first thing a customer sees when they message your page for the first time. Start with a friendly greeting: "Hi! Welcome to [Business Name]. How can we help you today?" Add Quick Reply buttons for your main scenarios: "View Menu," "Make a Reservation," "Track My Order," "Talk to Our Team." Each button leads to a separate flow branch that you build out according to your conversation design from Lesson 3. Minute 45-75: Build your FAQ automation. Set up keyword triggers — when a customer types "menu," "price," "magkano," "hours," "schedule," or "location," the bot automatically responds with the relevant information. ManyChat keyword triggers support multiple keywords per automation, so you can capture variations: "price," "prices," "pricing," "magkano," "how much," "presyo" all trigger the same pricing response. Add your product or service information as structured responses with images and buttons. Minute 75-100: Build your human handoff. Create a "Talk to a Human" option accessible from every flow. When triggered, the bot sends an internal notification to the page admin (via Messenger or email) and tells the customer: "Our team member will be with you shortly. Average response time: 10 minutes during business hours (9 AM - 6 PM)." Set business hours so the bot can manage expectations: "Our team is offline right now but will respond first thing tomorrow at 9 AM. In the meantime, here are some helpful links." Minute 100-120: Test and refine. Open Messenger on your phone and message your own page. Go through every flow path as if you were a customer. Test keyword triggers with different phrasings, including common Taglish variations. Fix any dead ends, unclear responses, or missing branches. Have a friend test it without telling them how it works — watch where they get confused. The critical number: ManyChat reports that Facebook Pages with active chatbots see a 40% increase in customer engagement and a 25% reduction in response time. For your future clients, these metrics translate directly into more sales and happier customers.',
  'Build your chatbot now: (1) Open ManyChat and connect to your Facebook Page (create a test page if you prefer not to use your personal one). (2) Build the complete welcome flow with at least 4 Quick Reply options based on your conversation design. (3) Set up at least 5 keyword triggers covering the most common customer inquiries — include both English and Filipino variations. (4) Add a human handoff flow with business hours messaging. (5) Test thoroughly: message your page from your personal Messenger account. Go through every path. Fix every issue. Then send the page link to 2 friends and ask them to try messaging — observe where they succeed and where they get stuck. Document any improvements needed.',
  'How did it feel to see your chatbot responding to real messages? Was building in ManyChat easier or harder than you expected? Where did your friends get stuck when testing — what does that teach you about conversation design assumptions?',
  4
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Chatbot Foundations';

-- Lesson 5
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Measuring Chatbot Performance',
  'Building a chatbot is step one. Proving it works — with data — is what keeps clients paying and generates referrals. According to a 2025 Intercom report, businesses that track chatbot metrics and optimize monthly see 45% better results than those who "set and forget." Your ability to measure, report, and improve chatbot performance is what separates a ₱5,000 one-time project from a ₱10,000/month retainer. The five metrics that matter: Response Rate — the percentage of incoming messages that receive an automated response. Target: 85%+. If your chatbot handles fewer than 85% of messages, there are gaps in your keyword triggers and conversation flows that need fixing. ManyChat and Tidio both track this automatically. Resolution Rate — the percentage of conversations that are fully resolved by the chatbot without human intervention. Target: 60-70%. Not every conversation should be automated — complex issues need humans — but routine inquiries (hours, pricing, product info, order status) should be handled entirely by the bot. A low resolution rate means your flows are incomplete or your fallback triggers too early. Customer Satisfaction — measured through a simple end-of-conversation survey. After the bot resolves a query, ask: "Was this helpful? Yes / No." Track the ratio. Target: 80%+ "Yes" responses. Low satisfaction often indicates responses are too generic, too slow, or missing the actual information the customer needs. Drop-off Points — where in the conversation flow do customers stop responding? ManyChat analytics show exactly where users abandon the flow. If 50% of users drop off at the third question, that question is either confusing, irrelevant, or asking too much. Simplify, restructure, or skip it. Human Handoff Volume — how many conversations get escalated to a human agent and for what reasons. Track these in a spreadsheet: date, customer inquiry, reason for handoff. Patterns emerge quickly — if 30% of handoffs are about delivery tracking, build a delivery tracking flow. If 20% are complaints about a specific product, flag it for the client. This data is gold for both chatbot improvement and business intelligence. Reporting for clients: create a monthly report template with these 5 metrics, month-over-month trends, top 10 customer inquiries (what people ask most), improvement actions taken, and recommendations for next month. Deliver this report as a professional PDF (design it in Canva) on the 1st of every month. This report is your retention tool — it makes your value visible and gives the client confidence that their chatbot is actively managed and improving. Clients who receive monthly chatbot reports retain at 85% compared to 50% for those who do not receive regular updates.',
  'Set up your measurement system: (1) In ManyChat, navigate to Analytics and explore every metric available — response rate, user engagement, flow completion rates, and keyword performance. Screenshot the dashboard. (2) Create a monthly reporting template in Canva or Google Slides with sections for: key metrics summary, top performing flows, drop-off analysis, human handoff summary, and next month recommendations. (3) If you built a chatbot in Lesson 4, run it for 48 hours and collect initial data. Even with low volume, note the patterns. (4) Create a Google Sheet for tracking human handoffs: date, customer name or ID, inquiry type, reason for escalation, resolution, and time to resolve. (5) Using your chatbot data (or sample data), complete one full monthly report. This becomes a portfolio piece showing clients that you do not just build bots — you manage and optimize them.',
  'How does measuring chatbot performance change your perspective on the value you provide? Which of the five metrics surprised you most in terms of importance? How would presenting a professional monthly report to a client build trust and justify ongoing fees?',
  5
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Chatbot Foundations';


-- ============================================================
-- MODULE 2 LESSONS: Building with Tidio and ManyChat
-- ============================================================

-- Lesson 1
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'ManyChat Deep Dive',
  'ManyChat is the most widely used Messenger automation platform in the Philippines, and mastering it deeply — beyond basic flows — is what separates a ₱5,000 chatbot builder from a ₱30,000 automation specialist. In this lesson, you will build a complete e-commerce customer service bot that handles the full customer lifecycle: product discovery, purchase facilitation, order tracking, and post-purchase support. Advanced ManyChat features you need to master: Automation Flows are the backbone — multi-step sequences triggered by user actions. A sophisticated e-commerce flow starts with a product catalog browser (images, descriptions, prices displayed in a carousel), leads to a size or variant selector, captures the order via structured questions, confirms details, and provides payment instructions (GCash, Maya, bank transfer — the dominant payment methods in PH). Keyword Automation goes beyond simple triggers. Use Regular Expressions (regex) for flexible matching: "order" OR "track" OR "status" OR "delivery" OR "nasaan" OR "where" all route to the order tracking flow. ManyChat supports up to 10 keywords per automation — cover English, Filipino, and common abbreviations. Sequences are scheduled message series — like email sequences but in Messenger. Use them for: post-purchase follow-up (Day 1: order confirmation, Day 3: delivery update, Day 7: satisfaction check), abandoned cart recovery (customer viewed products but did not complete purchase — nudge after 24 hours), and re-engagement (customers who have not interacted in 30 days get a "We miss you" message with a special offer). Growth Tools are how you drive people into your Messenger bot. The most powerful for Philippine businesses: Comment Growth Tool — when someone comments on a Facebook post, the bot automatically sends them a DM. Set up a post like "Comment MENU to get our full menu sent to your inbox." This converts public engagement into private conversations at scale. Filipino audiences love this mechanic — engagement rates of 15-25% are common. Custom Fields and Tags let you segment your audience. Tag customers by: purchase history, product interests, location, language preference (English vs Filipino vs Bisaya), and customer value (new, repeat, VIP). Segmentation enables personalized messaging that feels one-to-one even at scale. The complete e-commerce bot you are building today handles: product browsing, order placement, payment confirmation, delivery tracking, returns and exchanges, FAQ, and customer feedback. It replaces 70-80% of manual Messenger conversations for the average Filipino online seller, saving 3-5 hours of daily customer service work.',
  'Build a complete e-commerce chatbot in ManyChat: (1) Create a product catalog flow — add at least 5 products with images, descriptions, and prices in a carousel format. Each product should have a "Buy Now" button that starts the order flow. (2) Build the order flow: collect customer name, delivery address (with Philippine address format — barangay, city, province, zip), payment method (GCash, Maya, BDO/BPI transfer), and order confirmation. (3) Set up 3 keyword automations: "order status" + Filipino variations, "menu" or "products" + Filipino variations, and "help" or "customer service" + Filipino variations. (4) Create a Comment Growth Tool: write a sample Facebook post and set up the auto-DM that triggers when someone comments with a specific keyword. (5) Build a 3-message post-purchase sequence: order confirmation, delivery update (sent after 2 days), and satisfaction survey (sent after 5 days).',
  'How does building a full e-commerce bot compare to the simple FAQ bot from the previous module? Which advanced feature (sequences, growth tools, or custom fields) do you think would have the biggest impact for a Filipino online seller? How confident are you now in building chatbots for paying clients?',
  1
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Building with Tidio and ManyChat';

-- Lesson 2
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Tidio for Website Chat',
  'While ManyChat dominates Facebook Messenger automation, Tidio is the superior choice for website-based customer service — and the Philippine e-commerce landscape is rapidly shifting toward independent websites. According to a 2025 Globe Business report, 45% of Filipino online sellers now have their own Shopify or WordPress website in addition to their Shopee and Lazada stores, driven by the desire to avoid marketplace fees (which average 12-15% on Shopee and Lazada). These website owners need on-site customer service, and Tidio provides it. Tidio installation is remarkably simple: a single line of JavaScript code added to any website, or a one-click plugin for Shopify and WordPress. The chat widget appears in the bottom-right corner — familiar to any internet user — and begins engaging visitors immediately. For Shopify stores (the fastest-growing e-commerce platform in PH with a 67% year-over-year growth in Filipino merchants), Tidio integrates natively with product catalogs, order data, and customer profiles. Key Tidio features for Philippine businesses: AI Responses powered by Tidio built-in AI learn from your FAQ content and product pages. Upload a document with common questions and answers, and Tidio AI handles them conversationally. Unlike rule-based chatbots that only respond to exact keywords, AI responses understand intent — "When do you guys close?" and "What time is last order?" both trigger the business hours response. Visitor Tracking shows you who is on the website right now, what pages they are viewing, how long they have been browsing, and their location. For an e-commerce store, this is powerful: if someone has been looking at a product page for 3 minutes, trigger a proactive message: "Hi! I see you are looking at our [product]. Any questions? We have free shipping for orders over ₱1,500." This proactive engagement converts browsers into buyers — Tidio reports a 30% increase in conversion rates for stores using proactive triggers. Live Chat with Bot Handoff combines automation with human support. The bot handles routine queries (80% of volume), and complex questions are seamlessly transferred to a live agent. The customer does not feel the transition — the conversation continues in the same window. Chatbot Templates save time: Tidio offers pre-built templates for e-commerce (product recommendations, order tracking), lead generation (contact form, newsletter signup), and customer support (FAQ, complaint handling). Customize these templates instead of building from scratch — 30 minutes versus 3 hours. Multi-language support: configure different language responses based on customer browser language. For Philippine businesses, set English as default with Filipino as an option — many customers browse in English but prefer to chat in Filipino.',
  'Build a complete Tidio website chatbot: (1) Create a free test website on Shopify (14-day free trial) or WordPress.com (free tier). Add 3-5 products with images and descriptions. (2) Install Tidio on your test website — follow the one-click installation for your platform. (3) Configure AI Responses: write a FAQ document (10+ questions and answers) and upload it to Tidio AI training. Test with 5 different phrasings of common questions to see if AI handles them. (4) Set up 2 proactive visitor triggers: one for product page visitors (after 2 minutes of browsing) and one for cart page visitors (to prevent abandonment). (5) Configure the live chat handoff: set business hours, offline message, and the transition message when a bot escalates to a human agent. Test the entire system by visiting your website as a customer.',
  'How does website chat feel different from Messenger chat as a customer experience? Which Tidio feature do you think adds the most value for Filipino e-commerce businesses? How could you combine Tidio (website) and ManyChat (Messenger) to offer a comprehensive customer service solution?',
  2
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Building with Tidio and ManyChat';

-- Lesson 3
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Multi-Platform Chatbots',
  'Filipino consumers do not use a single platform — they discover brands on TikTok, browse products on Instagram, ask questions on Messenger, and complete purchases on a website. A 2025 We Are Social Philippines report found that the average Filipino uses 8.7 different social media platforms. Your clients need customer service that meets customers wherever they are, without requiring separate management for each channel. Multi-platform chatbot strategy means building one unified system that serves customers across Facebook Messenger, Instagram DMs, website chat, and potentially WhatsApp and Viber. Unified inbox management is the key concept. Instead of checking Messenger, Instagram, and website chat separately — which is how most Filipino business owners currently operate — a unified inbox collects all conversations in one place. ManyChat Pro ($15/month) provides a unified inbox for Messenger and Instagram. Tidio ($29/month) unifies website chat, Messenger, and Instagram. For more advanced setups, tools like Respond.io (starting at $79/month) and Sleekflow (popular in Southeast Asia, starting at $79/month) connect all channels including WhatsApp, Viber, LINE, and even Shopee chat. Building cross-platform consistency: your chatbot responses should maintain the same brand voice, information accuracy, and service quality regardless of which platform the customer uses. Create a single master conversation flow document that covers all scenarios. Adapt the format for each platform: Messenger allows rich carousels, buttons, and quick replies. Instagram DMs support buttons and images but with different constraints. Website chat (Tidio) allows the most flexibility — videos, forms, and rich media. Platform-specific optimizations for the Philippine market: Facebook Messenger remains the primary customer service channel for 70% of Filipino businesses. Optimize for speed — quick replies and buttons reduce typing. Instagram DMs are growing fastest among 18-30 year olds in Metro Manila, Cebu, and Davao. Visual product catalogs and story-to-DM automation work well here. Website chat converts highest for considered purchases (electronics, furniture, services) where customers need more information before buying. WhatsApp is gaining ground in the Philippines — from 23% penetration in 2023 to 38% in 2025 — especially for B2B communication and professional services. Viber remains popular among older Filipinos (35+) and for group communications. The multi-platform service offering: charge ₱15,000-₱30,000 for initial setup across 3+ platforms, plus ₱5,000-₱12,000/month for ongoing management and optimization. This premium positioning reflects the complexity and value of unified customer service — businesses that implement multi-platform chatbots see a 52% increase in customer satisfaction according to Zendesk research.',
  'Build a multi-platform chatbot system: (1) Connect both ManyChat (Messenger + Instagram) and Tidio (website) for the same business — use your test accounts from previous lessons. (2) Create a master conversation flow document in Google Docs that covers all customer scenarios for one business. Adapt this flow for each platform, noting format differences. (3) Build identical FAQ automation on both ManyChat and Tidio — same questions, same answers, adapted for each platform format. (4) Set up a unified monitoring system: open ManyChat and Tidio dashboards side by side. Practice switching between platforms to respond to messages. Note the friction points. (5) Research Respond.io or Sleekflow — sign up for a free trial and explore how a true unified inbox works. Compare the experience to managing ManyChat and Tidio separately.',
  'How does managing multiple chatbot platforms simultaneously feel — is it manageable or overwhelming? What would a unified inbox change about the management experience? How would you price a multi-platform chatbot service versus a single-platform bot?',
  3
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Building with Tidio and ManyChat';

-- Lesson 4
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'E-Commerce Chatbot Templates',
  'E-commerce is the sweet spot for chatbot services in the Philippines. The Philippine e-commerce market reached ₱845 billion in 2025 (a 25% increase from 2024), with over 73 million Filipino online shoppers. Every online seller — from solo Shopee merchants to growing D2C brands — faces the same customer service challenges: repetitive questions about products, order status inquiries, return and exchange requests, and payment confirmation. Building reusable chatbot templates for these common scenarios lets you deploy client bots in hours instead of days, dramatically increasing your profitability. Template 1: Order Tracking Flow. This is the single most requested chatbot feature for Filipino e-commerce businesses. The flow: Customer says "order status" or "track my order" or "nasaan order ko" → Bot asks for order number or phone number → Bot checks order database (via Google Sheets integration or API) → Bot displays order status with estimated delivery date. For simple implementations without API integration, the bot asks for the order number and notifies the store owner to respond with an update within 30 minutes. Even this basic version saves time because it captures and organizes inquiries automatically. Template 2: Product Recommendation Engine. Customer says "I am looking for a gift" or "What do you recommend?" → Bot asks qualifying questions: "Who is it for?" (buttons: For Me / For a Gift), "What is your budget?" (buttons: Under ₱500 / ₱500-₱1,000 / Over ₱1,000), "What category?" (buttons based on store categories) → Bot displays 3-5 matching products from a pre-loaded catalog. This flow replaces the manual back-and-forth that costs sellers 10-15 minutes per conversation. Template 3: Size and Fit Guide. Critical for clothing and accessories sellers — size questions account for 30% of pre-purchase inquiries in Philippine fashion e-commerce. Bot presents a visual size chart, asks for measurements (bust, waist, hips in centimeters), and recommends the correct size. Reduces returns by an estimated 20%. Template 4: Returns and Exchange Process. Customer says "return" or "exchange" or "refund" → Bot asks for order number, reason for return (buttons: Wrong Size / Defective / Changed Mind / Other), and photo of the item → Bot confirms the return request and provides instructions (where to ship, what to include, timeline for refund). This automates the most emotionally charged customer interaction and ensures consistent, policy-compliant handling. Template 5: Payment Confirmation Flow. After purchase, customer sends GCash or Maya payment screenshot → Bot confirms receipt with an order reference number and estimated delivery date. For COD (Cash on Delivery, still used by 55% of Filipino online shoppers), bot confirms the order and provides delivery timeline. These five templates cover 80-85% of all e-commerce customer service interactions. Building them once and customizing for each client takes 2-4 hours per deployment versus 15-20 hours building from scratch each time.',
  'Build your e-commerce template library: (1) In ManyChat, build the Order Tracking Flow template — include all keyword triggers (English and Filipino variations), order number capture, and store notification. Save it as a reusable template. (2) Build the Product Recommendation Flow — create a 3-question qualifier that leads to product suggestions. Use placeholder products for now. (3) Build the Returns and Exchange Flow — include reason selection, photo upload prompt, and confirmation message. (4) Test all three templates by messaging your bot as different types of customers — a happy buyer checking their order, a confused shopper needing recommendations, and an unhappy customer wanting a return. (5) Document each template in a Google Doc: include the flow diagram, all text content, keyword triggers, and customization notes for different business types. This document is your deployment guide for client projects.',
  'Which template do you think Filipino online sellers would find most valuable — and which would they pay the most for? How does having ready-made templates change your project pricing and delivery timeline? What additional templates would be useful for the Philippine e-commerce market?',
  4
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Building with Tidio and ManyChat';

-- Lesson 5
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Lead Generation Bots',
  'Lead generation — capturing potential customer information before they are ready to buy — is one of the highest-value chatbot applications, and Filipino businesses are only beginning to understand its power. A 2025 HubSpot Southeast Asia report found that businesses using chatbots for lead capture see a 67% higher lead-to-customer conversion rate compared to traditional web forms. In the Philippines, where 76% of online interactions start on mobile and typing long forms is painful on small screens, chatbot-based lead capture feels natural and frictionless. The lead generation bot concept: instead of asking a website visitor to fill out a contact form (which 90% of people abandon), you engage them in a friendly conversation that collects the same information. "Hi! Looking for our catering services? Let me help you get a quick quote. How many guests are you expecting?" is infinitely more engaging than a 7-field form. The information you capture becomes a qualified lead delivered directly to the business owner. Lead gen bot applications for Philippine businesses: Real Estate — "Looking for a condo in BGC? Let me help you find the right unit. What is your budget range?" Captures budget, preferred location, unit type, and contact number. Each qualified lead is worth ₱5,000-₱20,000 to a real estate agent. Clinics and Dental — "Ready to book an appointment? What service are you interested in?" Captures service type, preferred date and time, insurance information, and contact details. Reduces no-shows by 35% when combined with appointment reminders. Events and Catering — "Planning an event? Let me get you a quick quote." Captures event type, date, guest count, budget, venue, and dietary requirements. Replaces 15-minute phone calls with 2-minute chat interactions. Service Businesses (salons, spas, gyms, tutoring) — "Want to try our new treatment? Let me check availability for you." Captures service interest, preferred time, and contact information. CRM integration: lead data is only valuable if it goes somewhere useful. ManyChat integrates with Google Sheets (free), Mailchimp, and HubSpot CRM (free tier). Set up automatic export: every lead captured by the bot is immediately added to a spreadsheet or CRM with timestamp, source, and all collected information. The business owner opens their spreadsheet each morning and sees new leads ready to follow up. Revenue impact calculations for your client pitch: if the bot captures 10 qualified leads per week and the business converts 30% of leads (reasonable for warm chatbot leads), that is 3 new customers per week. At an average customer value of ₱2,000, the bot generates ₱6,000 per week or ₱24,000 per month in new revenue. Your setup fee of ₱15,000 pays for itself in the first 3 weeks. Your monthly management fee of ₱5,000 is covered by 2-3 new customers. This math makes your service an easy "yes" for any business owner who understands numbers.',
  'Build a lead generation chatbot: (1) Choose a business type — real estate, clinic, catering, or service business. (2) Build a conversational lead capture flow in ManyChat: 4-6 qualifying questions that feel like a friendly conversation, not a form. End with capturing name, phone number (mobile — required for GCash/Maya follow-up), and email. (3) Connect the bot to Google Sheets via ManyChat Zapier integration (or ManyChat native Google Sheets integration). Every captured lead should automatically appear in a spreadsheet with all collected information plus timestamp. (4) Build an automated follow-up: after lead capture, send a confirmation message immediately, then a follow-up message after 24 hours if they have not been contacted by the business. (5) Calculate the ROI for a real business: estimate leads per week, conversion rate, average customer value, and monthly revenue generated. Document this calculation — it becomes the core of your sales pitch.',
  'How does conversational lead capture feel compared to traditional forms? Which business type would benefit most from a lead generation bot in your local area? How does being able to show ROI calculations change the way you approach selling chatbot services?',
  5
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Building with Tidio and ManyChat';


-- ============================================================
-- MODULE 3 LESSONS: AI-Powered Smart Support
-- ============================================================

-- Lesson 1
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Integrating Claude and GPT into Customer Service',
  'Rule-based chatbots handle structured, predictable conversations well — but real customer service is messy. Customers ask questions in unexpected ways, combine multiple requests in one message, use slang and abbreviations, and express emotions that keywords cannot capture. This is where AI language models like Claude and GPT transform customer service from "basic automation" to "intelligent assistance." According to a 2025 Gartner report, AI-powered customer service solutions reduce handling time by 40% and increase first-contact resolution by 25% compared to rule-based chatbots. The key concept is the hybrid approach: use rule-based automation (ManyChat, Tidio) for structured interactions (product catalogs, order tracking, appointment booking) where the conversation follows a predictable path, and use AI (Claude or GPT) for unstructured interactions (product questions, complaints, recommendations) where the customer input is unpredictable. API integration simplified: you do not need to be a developer to connect AI to your chatbots. The simplest approach uses Zapier or Make (formerly Integromat) as a bridge. Customer sends a message → ManyChat triggers a Zapier webhook → Zapier sends the message to Claude API or GPT API → API returns a response → Zapier sends the response back to ManyChat → Customer receives an intelligent answer. Total setup time: 1-2 hours. Cost: Zapier free tier (100 tasks/month) plus API costs (approximately $0.002-$0.01 per conversation, or less than ₱1). For higher volume, ManyChat Pro allows direct API connections through their External Request feature — no Zapier needed. When to use AI versus rules: Use rules when: the answer is always the same (store hours, location, pricing), the conversation needs buttons and carousels (product browsing), and when you need guaranteed accuracy (order numbers, payment instructions). Use AI when: the question is open-ended ("What do you recommend for oily skin?"), the customer describes a problem ("My order arrived damaged and I am really frustrated"), multiple topics are combined in one message, or the conversation requires empathy and nuance. Safety guardrails are essential: AI can hallucinate — it might make up product information, pricing, or policies. Always include a system prompt that restricts the AI to only use information from the business knowledge base. Add a disclaimer in complex situations: "Based on what I know, here is my suggestion. For order-specific or account-specific questions, let me connect you with our team." Monitor AI responses daily during the first 2 weeks of deployment and weekly thereafter. Flag and correct any inaccurate responses. This quality control is part of your ongoing service — and justifies monthly retainer fees of ₱8,000-₱15,000.',
  'Set up your first AI-powered chatbot integration: (1) Create a Zapier account (free tier) at zapier.com. (2) Get a Claude API key from console.anthropic.com (free trial credits available) or an OpenAI API key from platform.openai.com. (3) In ManyChat, create a new flow where a customer asks a product question. Instead of a static response, add an External Request step that sends the customer message to a Zapier webhook. (4) In Zapier, create a zap: Webhook trigger → Claude or GPT API call → Webhook response back to ManyChat. Include a system prompt that restricts the AI to answering only about the business products and policies. (5) Test the integration: ask your bot various product questions in different phrasings. Note which questions get accurate answers and which need improvement in the system prompt. Document the entire setup process as a replicable SOP.',
  'How does the AI-powered response quality compare to the rule-based responses you built earlier? What surprised you most about how the AI handled unexpected questions? What guardrails would you add to ensure the AI never gives harmful or inaccurate information to customers?',
  1
from public.modules m where m.title = 'AI-Powered Smart Support';

-- Lesson 2
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Training AI on Your Client Business',
  'An AI customer service agent is only as good as the knowledge you give it. A generic AI can answer general questions about anything, but a trained AI answers specific questions about your client business with accuracy and brand voice. According to a 2025 Forrester study, AI chatbots trained on business-specific knowledge bases achieve 89% accuracy rates compared to 52% for generic AI responses. The difference is dramatic — and it is the value you provide as an automation specialist. Building a business knowledge base: Start by collecting every piece of information a customer might ask about. Product catalog — every product with full details: name, description, price, sizes, colors, materials, care instructions, shipping weight. Store information — hours, location (with landmarks for Filipino navigation — "beside Mercury Drug on Rizal Avenue"), parking, accessibility, WiFi availability. Policies — returns (timeline, conditions, process), shipping (options, costs, delivery estimates by region), payment methods (GCash, Maya, credit card, COD, installment options), warranty, and loyalty program. FAQ compilation — collect the 50 most frequently asked questions from the business social media messages, reviews, and staff. Common customer scenarios — "I want to change my order," "My delivery is late," "I received the wrong item," "Do you have this in a different size?" Staff and brand information — brand story, founding year, mission, team names for human handoff. Format this information as a structured document — Claude and GPT perform significantly better when knowledge is organized with clear headers, bullet points, and consistent formatting. A well-structured knowledge base document typically runs 3,000-8,000 words for a small business and 10,000-20,000 words for a medium business. The system prompt is your control mechanism. It tells the AI: who it is ("You are Sara, the customer service assistant for Bloom Skincare PH"), what it knows ("Use ONLY the following product information and policies to answer customer questions"), how it speaks ("Respond in friendly, conversational Taglish. Use po and opo. Keep responses under 3 sentences unless the question requires more detail"), and what it cannot do ("Never make up product information. Never promise discounts without authorization. If unsure, say: Let me check with our team and get back to you within 30 minutes"). Making AI sound like the brand: every business has a voice. A luxury spa talks differently from a streetwear brand. Include 5-10 example conversations in your system prompt — real exchanges between the business and customers that demonstrate the ideal tone, vocabulary, and style. Claude and GPT learn patterns from examples better than from abstract descriptions.',
  'Build a complete knowledge base for a business: (1) Choose a real local business (with their permission) or create a detailed fictional one. (2) Create a knowledge base document in Google Docs organized with clear headers: About Us, Products/Services (with full details for at least 10 items), Policies (returns, shipping, payments), FAQ (at least 20 questions and answers), and Contact Information. Aim for 3,000+ words. (3) Write a detailed system prompt (500+ words) that defines the AI personality, knowledge boundaries, tone guidelines, and 5 example conversations. (4) Test your knowledge base: feed it to Claude or GPT via their chat interfaces with your system prompt. Ask 20 different customer questions and rate each response for accuracy (1-10) and tone (1-10). (5) Refine: for any response scoring below 7, identify what was missing from the knowledge base or system prompt and add it. Repeat testing until you achieve 8+ average across all responses.',
  'How much effort goes into building a quality knowledge base versus building the chatbot itself? What types of questions did the AI handle well, and which required additional training? How does this knowledge base creation process represent value that you can charge premium prices for?',
  2
from public.modules m where m.title = 'AI-Powered Smart Support';

-- Lesson 3
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Handling Complex Queries with AI',
  'Basic chatbot interactions are single-turn: customer asks a question, bot answers. Real customer service is multi-turn: "I ordered a dress last Tuesday, but I received the wrong color. I want to exchange it, but I also want to know if the blue version is available in medium. And can I pick it up from your Makati branch instead of having it delivered?" This single message contains four distinct requests — wrong order complaint, exchange request, product availability check, and pickup option inquiry. A well-trained AI handles all four in one coherent response. Multi-turn conversation management: the challenge is context retention — remembering what was said earlier in the conversation. Claude and GPT both maintain context within a conversation, but when integrated through chatbot platforms, each message may be processed independently (losing context). The solution: pass conversation history with each API call. In your Zapier or ManyChat integration, store the last 5-10 messages and include them in every API request. This gives the AI the full picture. Implementation: use ManyChat Custom Fields to store a "conversation_history" variable. Each time the customer sends a message, append it to the history. Send the full history to the AI with each request. The AI sees: "Customer said: [message 1], Bot replied: [reply 1], Customer said: [message 2]" — and responds with full context. Escalation triggers: AI should not handle everything. Define clear escalation rules: emotional intensity (if the customer uses words like "angry," "disappointed," "worst," "never again," or Filipino equivalents like "bwisit," "nakakagalit," "sayang"), financial requests (refunds over ₱1,000, custom pricing, bulk order negotiations), legal mentions (warranty claims, consumer protection, DTI complaints), and technical failures (payment processing errors, account access issues). When triggered, the AI should: acknowledge the issue empathetically ("I completely understand your frustration, and I am sorry for this experience"), capture all relevant details (order number, issue description, preferred resolution), and smoothly hand off ("I am connecting you with [Team Lead Name] who has the authority to resolve this for you right away. They have your full case details"). Real example from a Philippine e-commerce business: A customer messages at 11 PM: "Hi. I ordered a birthday gift for my daughter and it was supposed to arrive today but it did not come. Her birthday is tomorrow and I am really upset." The AI responds: "I am so sorry to hear that, and I completely understand how upsetting this must be, especially with your daughter birthday tomorrow. Let me check on your order right away. Can you please share your order number so I can look into the delivery status? I will also flag this as urgent with our logistics team." This response demonstrates empathy, takes immediate action, and does not make promises it cannot keep. It is exactly what a skilled human agent would write — but it responds in 3 seconds instead of 3 hours.',
  'Build multi-turn conversation handling: (1) In your ManyChat bot, set up a Custom Field called "conversation_history" (text type). Create a flow that appends each customer message and bot response to this field. (2) Modify your AI integration to include the conversation_history in every API call to Claude or GPT. Test with a 5-message back-and-forth conversation — does the AI remember what was discussed earlier? (3) Create an escalation trigger system: list 10 keywords and phrases (in English and Filipino) that should trigger human handoff. Implement these as conditions in your ManyChat flow that redirect to a human agent before the AI responds. (4) Write and test 3 complex customer scenarios that combine multiple requests in one message. Feed each to your AI and evaluate how well it handles the complexity. (5) Create a "Complex Query Handling" SOP document that your future team members can follow — include escalation rules, response guidelines, and example conversations.',
  'How did the AI perform when handling multi-topic customer messages compared to simple single-question interactions? What emotional intelligence did you observe in AI responses — and where did it fall short? How would you explain the value of multi-turn, context-aware AI to a client who currently uses basic keyword chatbots?',
  3
from public.modules m where m.title = 'AI-Powered Smart Support';

-- Lesson 4
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Multilingual Support with AI',
  'The Philippines has 175 living languages. While Filipino (based on Tagalog) and English are the official languages, daily communication — especially customer service — happens in Taglish (Tagalog-English mix), Bisaya (spoken by 20 million people in Visayas and Mindanao), Ilocano (8 million speakers in Northern Luzon), Hiligaynon (7 million speakers in Western Visayas), and Waray (3.6 million speakers in Eastern Visayas). A chatbot that only speaks English misses the warmth and accessibility that Filipino customers expect. According to a 2025 Common Sense Advisory study adapted for the Philippine market, 72% of Filipino consumers are more likely to purchase from a brand that communicates in their preferred language. AI makes multilingual customer service feasible without hiring agents for every language. Claude and GPT both handle Filipino, Bisaya, and other major Philippine languages well. The quality varies: English responses are near-perfect, Filipino (Tagalog) is very good with occasional unnatural phrasing, Bisaya is good for common phrases but can be awkward for complex sentences, and other regional languages are functional but require more human review. Auto-detection is the first layer: when a customer messages in Bisaya ("Unsay presyo ani?"), the AI should detect the language and respond in Bisaya ("Ang presyo ani kay ₱599. Gusto ba nimo makahibaw pa ug dugang?"). Claude handles this natively — include in your system prompt: "Detect the customer language and respond in the same language. Supported languages: English, Filipino/Tagalog, Taglish, Bisaya/Cebuano. If unsure about the language, respond in English." Implementation approach for chatbot platforms: Method 1 (Simple) — add language detection to your AI system prompt. The AI automatically responds in the detected language. This works for Claude/GPT-powered responses but not for rule-based flows. Method 2 (Comprehensive) — at the start of the conversation, ask the customer: "How would you like to chat? English / Filipino / Bisaya." Store their preference as a Custom Field. Route them to language-specific conversation flows with pre-translated content. For AI-powered responses, include the language preference in the system prompt. Cultural nuances matter: direct translation is not enough. Filipino customer service uses "po" and "opo" for respect — critical for older customers. Bisaya communication tends to be more casual and direct. Ilocano speakers appreciate when you acknowledge their language even if the full conversation continues in Filipino. Addressing customers as "Kuya," "Ate," "Sir," or "Ma'am" varies by region and context. Train your AI on these nuances with example conversations in each language. The business value: multilingual chatbot support is a premium service. Most chatbot builders in the Philippines offer English-only bots. By offering Taglish + Bisaya support, you serve the 85% of Filipino consumers who prefer communicating in their native language. Add ₱5,000-₱10,000 per additional language to your project pricing. A trilingual chatbot (English + Filipino + Bisaya) commands ₱25,000-₱50,000 versus ₱15,000 for English-only.',
  'Build multilingual AI responses: (1) Update your AI system prompt to include language detection instructions and response guidelines for English, Filipino/Taglish, and Bisaya. Include 3 example conversations in each language demonstrating the correct tone and cultural nuances. (2) Test your AI with 5 customer questions in each language (15 total). Rate each response for: language accuracy (1-10), cultural appropriateness (1-10), and helpfulness (1-10). (3) Create a translation guide document for common chatbot phrases in all three languages — greetings, confirmations, error messages, handoff messages, and closing messages. This becomes your quick-reference when building multilingual flows. (4) In ManyChat, build a language selection flow at the start of the conversation that stores the customer preference and routes to language-specific content. (5) Identify 3 businesses in your area that serve multilingual customers (restaurants in tourist areas, nationwide e-commerce brands, BPO companies) — these are your ideal clients for multilingual chatbot services.',
  'How did AI perform across different Philippine languages — where was it strong and where did it struggle? What cultural nuances are hardest to capture in automated responses? How does offering multilingual support differentiate you from other chatbot builders in the market?',
  4
from public.modules m where m.title = 'AI-Powered Smart Support';

-- Lesson 5
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'AI Quality Control',
  'AI-powered customer service is powerful, but it is not infallible. Claude and GPT can hallucinate — confidently stating incorrect product information, making up policies that do not exist, or providing outdated pricing. In customer service, a single hallucinated response can cost a business a customer, trigger a refund demand, or create a social media crisis. A 2025 Stanford AI Index report found that even the best AI language models hallucinate in 3-8% of responses. In a business receiving 100 AI-handled messages per day, that means 3-8 potentially inaccurate responses daily. Your quality control system is what prevents these from reaching customers or, when they do, catches and corrects them quickly. The three-layer quality control framework: Layer 1 — Prevention. Design your system prompt to minimize hallucinations: restrict the AI to only use information from the knowledge base ("Only answer based on the information provided below. If the answer is not in the knowledge base, say: I do not have that information, but let me connect you with our team"), include specific instructions to never make up pricing, availability, or policy details, and add a confidence qualifier: "If you are less than 90% sure of your answer, acknowledge the uncertainty." Layer 2 — Detection. Monitor AI responses actively. During the first 2 weeks of deployment, review every AI response manually. Log each response in a spreadsheet: accurate / inaccurate / partially accurate. After 2 weeks, switch to sampling: review 20% of AI responses daily. Use ManyChat or Tidio analytics to flag conversations where customers responded negatively (keywords: "wrong," "that is not right," "incorrect," "you said," or Filipino equivalents: "mali," "hindi tama," "iba sinabi mo"). Set up a daily 15-minute review routine — this is non-negotiable for maintaining quality. Layer 3 — Correction. When you find an inaccurate response: immediately correct the conversation (apologize and provide accurate information), update the knowledge base to prevent the same error, adjust the system prompt if the error reveals a pattern, and document the error in a quality log with: date, customer message, AI response, correct answer, and root cause. The feedback loop: every correction makes the system better. After 30 days of active quality control, hallucination rates typically drop to under 1% because your knowledge base has been refined by real customer interactions. This continuous improvement is the ongoing service that justifies your monthly retainer. Avoiding hallucinations in the Philippine market specifically: always include current prices in Philippine Pesos (AI may try to convert from USD or use outdated prices), specify Philippine-specific policies (COD availability, GCash payment process, local delivery timelines by region), include local context (Philippine holidays, weather-related delays during typhoon season, local regulations), and update the knowledge base whenever the business changes products, pricing, or policies. Client communication about AI limitations: be transparent. Tell clients: "AI handles 85-90% of customer inquiries accurately. For the remaining 10-15%, we have human escalation and a quality monitoring system. No AI is perfect, but our quality control ensures continuous improvement." This honesty builds trust and sets realistic expectations.',
  'Implement a quality control system: (1) Set up a Quality Control spreadsheet in Google Sheets with columns: Date, Customer Message, AI Response, Accuracy Rating (1-10), Issue Identified, Correction Made, Knowledge Base Updated (Y/N). (2) If your AI chatbot is live, review the last 20 AI responses and rate each one. If it is not live, generate 20 test interactions and evaluate them. (3) Identify the top 3 categories of inaccurate or weak responses. For each, update your knowledge base with more specific information and refine your system prompt. (4) Re-test the same 20 questions after your improvements. Compare accuracy scores before and after. (5) Create a "Quality Control SOP" document that any team member could follow: daily review checklist, escalation criteria, knowledge base update process, and monthly quality report template. This SOP is essential for scaling your service.',
  'How did reviewing AI responses change your confidence in deploying AI for customer service? What patterns did you notice in the types of errors the AI made? How does having a systematic quality control process change the way you would pitch AI chatbot services to a cautious client?',
  5
from public.modules m where m.title = 'AI-Powered Smart Support';


-- ============================================================
-- MODULE 4 LESSONS: Analytics and Optimization
-- ============================================================

-- Lesson 1
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Customer Service Metrics That Matter',
  'What gets measured gets improved — and in customer service automation, the right metrics are the difference between a chatbot that saves money and one that quietly loses customers. According to a 2025 Freshdesk benchmark report for Southeast Asian businesses, companies that track customer service metrics systematically see 34% higher customer retention rates than those that rely on anecdotal feedback. For your automation clients, metrics prove ROI — and ROI is what keeps them paying your monthly retainer. The essential customer service metrics: Customer Satisfaction Score (CSAT) is the gold standard. At the end of each chatbot interaction, ask: "How would you rate your experience? Great / Okay / Not helpful." Calculate: (Great responses / Total responses) x 100. Philippine benchmark: 78% CSAT for businesses with chatbots versus 65% for those without. Target: 80%+ for your clients. First Response Time (FRT) measures how quickly customers get their first response. With chatbots, this should be under 5 seconds — a massive improvement over the 3-8 hour average for manual responses in Philippine SMEs. Track this for both automated and human-handled conversations. Resolution Time measures the total time from first customer message to issue resolution. For automated conversations: target under 3 minutes. For escalated conversations: target under 2 hours during business hours. Track separately for automated versus human-resolved to demonstrate chatbot efficiency. Ticket Volume is the total number of customer service conversations per day, week, and month. Track trends: is volume growing (business is growing), stable, or declining? Spikes indicate issues — a product recall, website bug, or viral complaint. Automated Resolution Rate is the percentage of conversations fully handled by the bot without human intervention. Target: 65-75%. Below 60% means your bot flows need improvement. Above 80% might mean the bot is not escalating conversations that should be handled by humans. Average Handle Time (AHT) measures how long each conversation takes from start to finish. Lower is better for simple queries, but complex issues need adequate time. A bot that rushes customers through complaints will reduce AHT but destroy CSAT. Balance efficiency with quality. Escalation Rate is the percentage of conversations handed off to human agents. Target: 25-35%. Below 20% may indicate the bot is answering questions it should escalate. Above 40% means the bot needs more training or better flows. Building a metrics dashboard: use Google Data Studio (free) connected to your Google Sheets tracking data to create a visual dashboard. Include: real-time CSAT score, daily ticket volume trend line, automated versus human resolution pie chart, average response and resolution times, and weekly escalation rate. This dashboard is both your internal optimization tool and your client reporting foundation. Update it weekly and share with clients monthly.',
  'Build your customer service metrics dashboard: (1) Create a Google Sheet with tabs for each metric: CSAT, Response Time, Resolution Time, Ticket Volume, Automated Resolution Rate, and Escalation Rate. Add columns for daily tracking. (2) If your chatbot is live, populate with real data from the past 7 days. If not, create realistic sample data for a fictional e-commerce business handling 30-50 messages per day. (3) Connect your Google Sheet to Google Data Studio (Looker Studio) and create a visual dashboard with 6 widgets — one for each metric. Include trend lines showing week-over-week changes. (4) Calculate the business impact: if your chatbot reduced average response time from 4 hours to 5 seconds, and this prevented 10 lost sales per week at ₱500 average order value, that is ₱20,000/month in recovered revenue. Document this calculation. (5) Format the dashboard for client presentation — add the client business name, your agency logo, and a clean professional design. Save as a template you can duplicate for each client.',
  'Which customer service metric do you think is most important to track for Filipino SMEs — and why? How does having a visual dashboard change the way you communicate your value to clients? What story does the data tell about the difference between human-only and bot-assisted customer service?',
  1
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Analytics and Optimization';

-- Lesson 2
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Finding Bottlenecks in Support Flows',
  'A chatbot that works perfectly in testing often reveals problems when real customers use it. Filipino customers type in unexpected ways, ask questions you never anticipated, and navigate flows differently than you designed. Finding and fixing these bottlenecks is the ongoing optimization work that justifies your monthly retainer — and it is where most chatbot builders fail because they treat deployment as a one-time project. According to a 2025 Chatbot Magazine analysis, chatbots that are optimized monthly retain 3.2x more clients than those that are deployed and left unchanged. Common bottleneck types in Philippine chatbot deployments: Dead Ends — the customer reaches a point where the bot has no response and no redirect. This happens when a customer types something outside your planned scenarios. ManyChat analytics shows these as "unrecognized messages." Review unrecognized messages weekly — they reveal exactly what your bot is missing. Every dead end is a flow improvement opportunity. Circular Loops — the customer keeps getting redirected back to the same menu without resolution. This happens when flow logic is too rigid. Example: customer asks about a product that does not match any category button, keeps pressing "Other," and ends up at the main menu again. Solution: add a free-text option ("Just type your question and I will help") that routes to AI-powered response after 2 failed navigation attempts. High Drop-Off Points — ManyChat flow analytics shows where customers stop responding. If 40% of users abandon the conversation at the delivery address collection step, the step is too long, confusing, or asking for too much information at once. In the Philippines, address collection is notoriously complex (barangay names, subdivision names, landmarks) — simplify by asking for a Google Maps pin or offering address format examples. Language Mismatches — customer writes in Bisaya, bot responds in English. 15-20% of Filipino customers outside Metro Manila prefer their regional language. If your bot does not handle this, those customers disengage immediately. Payment Friction — COD (Cash on Delivery) is still the preferred payment method for 55% of Filipino online shoppers. If your bot payment flow focuses on GCash and credit card without prominently offering COD, you lose more than half your potential conversions. The bottleneck detection workflow: (1) Weekly: review all unrecognized messages and dead-end conversations. (2) Bi-weekly: analyze drop-off rates at each step of every flow. (3) Monthly: review CSAT feedback for patterns — low-rated conversations reveal pain points. (4) Quarterly: conduct a full conversation flow audit — go through every possible path as a customer and document issues. For each bottleneck found: diagnose the root cause, design the fix, implement in the chatbot platform, test thoroughly, and measure the impact after 1 week. Document everything — this improvement log becomes your monthly report to the client and demonstrates continuous value delivery.',
  'Conduct a bottleneck audit: (1) If your chatbot is live, export the last 7 days of conversation data from ManyChat or Tidio. If not, create 30 simulated conversations with various scenarios — including edge cases and unexpected inputs. (2) Identify all unrecognized messages and dead ends. Categorize them: missing flow, language issue, typo or abbreviation, or out-of-scope question. (3) Find the highest drop-off point in your main conversation flow. Analyze why customers stop responding at that step. Redesign the step to reduce friction. (4) Test your bot with 5 deliberate "break" attempts — type nonsense, mix languages, ask multi-part questions, express frustration. Document how the bot handles each case and where it fails. (5) Create a "Bottleneck Improvement Log" spreadsheet: Date Found, Bottleneck Type, Description, Root Cause, Fix Applied, Impact Measured. This becomes your ongoing optimization tracker.',
  'What was the most surprising bottleneck you discovered — one you would not have found without data analysis? How does thinking about edge cases and unexpected behavior change the way you design chatbot flows? Why do you think most chatbot builders skip ongoing optimization, and how does doing it give you a competitive advantage?',
  2
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Analytics and Optimization';

-- Lesson 3
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'A/B Testing Chatbot Responses',
  'A/B testing — showing different versions of a chatbot response to different users and measuring which performs better — is the scientific approach to optimization. Most chatbot builders rely on intuition: "I think this response sounds better." A/B testing removes guesswork and lets data decide. According to a 2025 Optimizely report, businesses that A/B test their chatbot conversations see a 21% improvement in conversion rates and 15% improvement in customer satisfaction within the first 3 months. What to A/B test in your chatbot: Greeting Messages — your welcome message sets the tone for the entire conversation. Test: Version A: "Hi! Welcome to [Store]. How can we help you today?" (formal, English) versus Version B: "Hello po! Glad you are here. What can I help you with?" (warm, Taglish). Track which version leads to more completed conversations. Response Length — Filipino customers on mobile (98% of Messenger users) have limited screen space. Test: Version A: detailed 4-sentence response with full explanation versus Version B: concise 2-sentence response with a "Want more details?" button. Track customer satisfaction and resolution rate for each. Call-to-Action Wording — the button text that drives the next action matters. Test: "Order Now" versus "Get Yours" versus "Add to Cart" versus "I Want This." In Philippine e-commerce, casual CTAs often outperform formal ones — but test rather than assume. Quick Reply Options — the number and wording of buttons. Test: 3 options versus 5 options, category names versus descriptive phrases ("Skin Care" versus "Help me with my skin"). Upsell Messages — after a customer shows interest in a product, test different upsell approaches. Version A: "Customers also bought [product]" versus Version B: "This pairs perfectly with [product] — ₱200 off when you get both." How to A/B test in ManyChat: ManyChat has a built-in Randomizer block. Set it to 50/50 split — half of customers see Version A, half see Version B. Track results using Custom Fields that tag which version each customer received. After 100+ interactions per version (statistical minimum for meaningful results), compare: conversion rate, CSAT score, drop-off rate, and average handle time. The version that performs better across your key metric becomes the permanent response. Then test a new variation against the winner — continuous improvement. Statistical significance simplified: do not make decisions on small samples. With 20 people per version, random variation can make the worse option look better. At 100+ per version, you can be 95% confident the difference is real. If Version A converts at 35% and Version B at 42% with 100+ users each, Version B is genuinely better. If the difference is less than 5% with fewer than 100 users, keep testing. The practical testing calendar: Week 1-2: test greeting messages. Week 3-4: test main FAQ response format. Week 5-6: test CTA wording. Week 7-8: test upsell messages. Repeat cycle with new variations each month. Report results to clients monthly — this data-driven optimization is a premium service worth ₱3,000-₱5,000 per month on top of your base management fee.',
  'Run your first A/B test: (1) In ManyChat, add a Randomizer block at the beginning of your most important flow (greeting or product inquiry). Create two versions of the first response — one formal English and one warm Taglish. (2) Set up tracking: create Custom Fields for "test_version" (A or B) and "test_outcome" (completed / dropped). Tag each user automatically based on which version they see. (3) Run the test with at least 20 interactions per version — ask friends, family, or use multiple Messenger accounts to generate volume. (4) Export results to a Google Sheet and calculate: completion rate per version, average conversation length per version, and any qualitative differences in customer responses. (5) Document your test: hypothesis ("Taglish greeting will have higher completion rate"), methodology, results, and conclusion. Add this to your portfolio as evidence of data-driven optimization skills.',
  'Did the A/B test results match your intuition, or did the data surprise you? How does the discipline of testing change the way you approach chatbot design? What other elements of your chatbot are you now eager to test?',
  3
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Analytics and Optimization';

-- Lesson 4
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Monthly Reporting for Clients',
  'The monthly report is the most important deliverable in your automation service — more important than the chatbot itself. A well-designed report demonstrates your value in clear, undeniable terms. It keeps clients informed, justifies their monthly investment, and preempts the "Why am I paying you every month?" question. According to a 2025 AgencyAnalytics survey, agencies that provide regular reporting retain clients 2.8x longer and charge 37% higher average monthly fees than those that do not. Your monthly chatbot performance report template: Page 1 — Executive Summary. Three bullet points maximum covering the most important results. Example: "Your chatbot handled 847 customer conversations this month, up 12% from last month. Customer satisfaction remained high at 83%. We identified and fixed 3 bottleneck areas that were causing 15% of customers to drop off." This page is for the busy business owner who might not read further — it communicates value in 15 seconds. Page 2 — Key Metrics Dashboard. Visual charts and graphs showing: total conversations (bar chart, month over month), automated resolution rate (percentage with trend arrow), customer satisfaction score (gauge chart), average response time (comparison: bot versus industry average), and escalation rate (pie chart: automated versus human-handled). Use Canva or Google Data Studio to create clean, branded visualizations. Page 3 — Top Insights. What did you learn from the data this month? "The most common customer question was about delivery time in Visayas — we recommend adding a region-specific delivery estimate to the bot." "Saturday afternoon saw 40% higher message volume than weekdays — consider extending human support coverage on weekends." These insights position you as a strategic advisor, not just a chatbot technician. Page 4 — Improvements Made. List every optimization you implemented: new conversation flows added, responses refined based on A/B testing, bottlenecks fixed with before and after metrics, and knowledge base updates. This proves active management and justifies your fee. Page 5 — Recommendations for Next Month. Three to five specific, actionable suggestions: "Add a product recommendation flow for your new arrivals." "Implement Bisaya language support — 23% of your customers message in Bisaya." "Create a loyalty program announcement flow for your VIP customers." These recommendations give the client a reason to continue the engagement and often lead to upsell opportunities (each recommendation is additional work you can charge for). Pricing your reporting and optimization service: the monthly report plus ongoing optimization should be included in your retainer (₱5,000-₱10,000/month). Never charge separately for reporting — it is your retention tool. The time investment is 2-3 hours per client per month. At ₱8,000/month for 3 hours of work, your effective hourly rate is over ₱2,600 — comparable to a senior professional salary in the Philippines.',
  'Create a complete monthly report: (1) Using your chatbot data (real or simulated), build a full 5-page monthly report following the template above. Design it in Canva with professional branding — your agency logo, client name, and consistent color scheme. (2) Create an Executive Summary that communicates value in 3 bullet points. (3) Build at least 3 visual charts using Google Data Studio, Canva charts, or Excel — total conversations trend, CSAT gauge, and automated versus human resolution split. (4) Write 3 specific, data-backed insights and 3 actionable recommendations for the next month. (5) Export as PDF and save as a reusable template. Create a Canva template that can be duplicated and customized for each client in under 30 minutes. Add this to your portfolio as a reporting sample.',
  'How does creating a professional report change the perceived value of your service? Which section of the report do you think clients care about most — metrics, insights, or recommendations? How would presenting this report in a 15-minute video call add even more value to the client relationship?',
  4
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Analytics and Optimization';

-- Lesson 5
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Reducing Costs While Improving Quality',
  'The ultimate value proposition of your automation service is doing more with less — helping clients reduce customer service costs while simultaneously improving the quality of customer experience. This is not a contradiction; it is the power of well-implemented automation. A 2025 McKinsey report on AI in Southeast Asian customer service found that businesses implementing chatbot automation reduce customer service operational costs by 30-50% while improving customer satisfaction scores by 15-25%. In the Philippines, where labor costs are already relatively low, the savings come from reduced overtime, fewer missed sales due to slow responses, and the ability to serve more customers without hiring additional staff. Cost reduction calculation for your client pitch: Map the current cost of manual customer service. A dedicated customer service agent in the Philippines earns ₱15,000-₱22,000/month. A small e-commerce business typically needs 1-2 agents handling 50-100 messages per day, 6 days per week. Total monthly cost: ₱15,000-₱44,000 in salary alone, plus benefits (13th month pay, SSS, PhilHealth, Pag-IBIG), workspace, internet, and equipment. Conservative monthly cost: ₱25,000-₱60,000. With your chatbot handling 65-75% of conversations, the same business needs one part-time agent (₱8,000-₱12,000/month) for escalated conversations only. Your chatbot service costs ₱10,000-₱15,000/month. Total new cost: ₱18,000-₱27,000/month. Savings: ₱7,000-₱33,000/month. That is the direct cost argument. The indirect value is even larger: 24/7 availability captures late-night shoppers (35% of Filipino e-commerce transactions happen between 8 PM and midnight), instant responses prevent cart abandonment, consistent quality eliminates bad-day customer service, and data collection enables business intelligence. Quality improvement metrics to track and present: Response time reduction — from hours to seconds. Consistency score — bot responses are 100% consistent versus human variance. Coverage expansion — from business hours only to 24/7. Error rate — bot error rate versus human error rate in providing accurate product information (humans average 5-8% information errors according to Zendesk data). Customer effort score — how easy is it for the customer to get help? Bot-assisted support typically scores 15-20% better because customers do not wait, repeat themselves, or get transferred multiple times. The optimization cycle that drives continuous improvement: Month 1 — deploy chatbot, establish baseline metrics. Month 2 — fix major bottlenecks, add missing flows based on unrecognized messages. Month 3 — implement A/B testing, begin optimizing response quality. Month 4-6 — add advanced features (multilingual support, AI integration, proactive engagement). Month 7-12 — focus on incremental optimization, upsell additional services, expand to new platforms. Each month, the system gets better and the client gets more value — which is why they keep paying. Present this trajectory during your initial sales conversation so clients understand they are investing in a system that appreciates over time, not a one-time product that depreciates.',
  'Build a cost-benefit analysis for a client: (1) Choose a real or fictional Filipino SME. Calculate their current customer service costs: agent salary, benefits (add 20% for mandatory Philippine employer contributions), workspace, tools, and opportunity cost of slow responses. (2) Model the automation scenario: chatbot handling 70% of conversations, part-time agent for escalations, your monthly service fee. Calculate total new cost and monthly savings. (3) Add indirect value: estimate the revenue impact of 24/7 availability, faster response times, and improved customer satisfaction. Use conservative estimates — 5% increase in conversion rate, 10% reduction in cart abandonment. (4) Create a professional 1-page cost-benefit summary in Canva — before versus after comparison with clear peso amounts. (5) Practice presenting this analysis out loud — you will use this exact format in sales conversations. Time yourself: aim to deliver the cost-benefit pitch in under 5 minutes, ending with your recommended package and monthly fee.',
  'How does presenting your service as a cost reduction tool change the sales conversation compared to presenting it as a technology product? What objections might a Filipino business owner raise, and how would your data address them? Looking at the 6-month optimization trajectory, how does long-term value creation change the way clients perceive your monthly retainer?',
  5
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Analytics and Optimization';


-- ============================================================
-- MODULE 5 LESSONS: Selling Automation Services
-- ============================================================

-- Lesson 1
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Your Automation Services Menu',
  'Packaging your chatbot and automation skills into clear, compelling service packages is what transforms technical ability into a profitable business. Filipino business owners do not buy "chatbots" — they buy solutions to problems: faster customer response, more sales, fewer missed inquiries, lower support costs. Your service menu must speak their language and connect directly to business outcomes. The automation services that sell best in the Philippine market: Package 1 — Starter Bot (₱15,000 one-time setup). Includes: Facebook Messenger chatbot with welcome flow, FAQ automation (up to 20 questions), keyword triggers (English and Filipino), basic lead capture, and 2 weeks of post-launch support. Target client: micro-businesses with 1-20 messages per day. Setup time: 8-12 hours. Profit margin: approximately 75% (your time is the primary cost). Package 2 — Professional Automation (₱30,000-₱50,000 one-time setup + ₱8,000/month maintenance). Includes: multi-platform chatbot (Messenger + Instagram + website), AI-powered responses via Claude or GPT integration, e-commerce flows (product catalog, order tracking, payment confirmation), multilingual support (English + Filipino), monthly optimization and reporting, and dedicated account manager (you). Target client: growing businesses with 20-100 messages per day. Setup time: 25-40 hours. This is your flagship package — high value, strong margins, and naturally leads to monthly retainers. Package 3 — Enterprise Automation (₱50,000-₱100,000 one-time + ₱15,000-₱25,000/month). Includes: everything in Professional, plus custom AI training on business knowledge base, advanced analytics dashboard, CRM integration, multi-language support (add Bisaya, Ilocano), staff training on chatbot management, and priority support with 4-hour response time. Target client: established businesses with 100+ messages per day, multiple locations, or complex product catalogs. Setup time: 60-100 hours. Package 4 — Monthly Maintenance Only (₱5,000-₱10,000/month). For clients who already have a chatbot (built by someone else or self-built) but need ongoing optimization, monitoring, and reporting. This is your easiest sell — low commitment, immediate value, and often upsells to a full rebuild. Pricing psychology for the Philippine market: always present all 4 packages together. The Enterprise package makes the Professional package look affordable by comparison (anchoring effect). Most clients choose Professional — which is exactly what you want. The Starter package captures budget-conscious clients who may upgrade later. The Maintenance package is your foot in the door for prospects who are not ready for a full build. Never discount your setup fee — instead, offer to waive the first month of maintenance for clients who sign a 6-month maintenance agreement. This preserves your project pricing while giving the client perceived savings of ₱5,000-₱10,000.',
  'Create your complete service menu: (1) Design a professional 3-4 page service menu PDF in Canva. Include: your agency logo and branding, all 4 packages with clear descriptions, pricing, and what is included. Add a "Why Choose Us" section highlighting your AI capabilities, Filipino market expertise, and quality guarantees. (2) Create a separate 1-page comparison chart showing all 4 packages side by side — features as rows, packages as columns, with checkmarks showing what is included in each. This visual makes it easy for clients to choose. (3) Write the FAQ section of your service menu: "How long does setup take?" "What do I need to provide?" "What happens after the chatbot is live?" "Can I cancel the monthly maintenance?" — answer all common objections. (4) Price-test your packages: share them with 3 business owners you know and ask for honest feedback on pricing. Adjust if needed. (5) Create a simple order form or booking link (Calendly for a discovery call, or Google Form for direct inquiries) and add it to every page of your service menu.',
  'Which package do you think will be your most popular seller in the Philippine market — and why? How does having a professional service menu change the way potential clients perceive you compared to just quoting prices over Messenger? What was the hardest part of pricing your services — and what would you need to see from the market to adjust your pricing confidently?',
  1
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Selling Automation Services';

-- Lesson 2
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Finding Your First Automation Client',
  'Your first automation client is the hardest to get and the most important. They become your case study, your testimonial source, and your proof of concept. According to a 2025 survey by the Philippine Online Sellers Society, 68% of Filipino e-commerce businesses are "interested" in chatbot automation but have not implemented it — primarily because they do not know where to start or who to hire. You are solving that problem by being visible, specific, and proactive. Target industries in the Philippines with the highest chatbot ROI: E-commerce Sellers (Shopee, Lazada, and D2C) handle the highest message volumes — 50-200+ daily. They lose sales every hour they do not respond. Your pitch: "I will build a chatbot that responds to your customers instantly, 24/7, and handles 70% of inquiries without you lifting a finger." Restaurants and Food Businesses get flooded with "What is your menu?" "Are you open?" "Do you deliver to [location]?" — the same 5 questions repeated hundreds of times. Your pitch: "Never answer the same question twice. Your chatbot handles menu inquiries, reservations, and delivery questions automatically." Service Businesses (salons, spas, clinics, gyms) need appointment booking, service information, and pricing inquiries handled. Your pitch: "Let customers book appointments through Messenger anytime, day or night. No more missed bookings because you were busy with another client." Real Estate Agents and Property Developers receive high-value leads that they lose due to slow response. Your pitch: "Every hour a lead waits for a response, the chance of conversion drops by 10%. My chatbot captures and qualifies leads in real-time, 24/7." Outreach strategies that work in the Philippines: The Free Audit — message a business on Facebook and note every problem with their current customer service: slow response time, no after-hours messaging, no FAQ automation, missed inquiries. Present this as a free "Customer Service Audit" with specific recommendations. 3 out of 10 businesses will engage with this approach. Facebook Group Networking — join Filipino business owner groups (there are hundreds with 10,000-100,000+ members). Do not sell directly. Instead, share helpful content: "3 reasons your Shopee store is losing sales in your DMs" or "How a Cebu bakery doubled their orders with a Messenger bot." Establish expertise, then let interested business owners come to you. Local Business Chambers — PCCI (Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry) chapters exist in every major city. Attend meetings, offer to present a 15-minute talk on "How AI is Changing Customer Service for Filipino Businesses," and collect contact information. Existing Network — your current Facebook friends include business owners, side hustlers, and people who know business owners. Post your services clearly: "I build chatbots for Filipino businesses. If your store gets more than 10 messages a day and you are tired of answering the same questions, message me. Free audit for the first 5 businesses." Direct, no hype, clear value proposition.',
  'Launch your client acquisition: (1) Identify 10 local businesses that would benefit from chatbot automation — restaurants, online sellers, salons, clinics. Visit their Facebook pages and note their response times and customer service gaps. (2) Create a "Free Customer Service Audit" template: a 1-page document that assesses response time, FAQ coverage, after-hours availability, and estimated lost revenue from slow responses. Complete this audit for your top 3 prospects. (3) Write 3 outreach messages tailored to different business types using Claude — restaurant, e-commerce seller, and service business. Lead with the problem, not the solution. (4) Send your audit and outreach message to your top 5 prospects this week. Track responses in your CRM spreadsheet. (5) Write and post one helpful piece of content about chatbot automation in a Filipino business Facebook group. Include a subtle call to action: "If you want me to audit your customer service for free, drop a comment or DM me."',
  'Which outreach method feels most natural to you — audits, Facebook groups, or direct network? What fears came up when you thought about approaching real businesses, and how did you push through them? What did you learn from the businesses that did not respond — and how will you adjust your approach?',
  2
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Selling Automation Services';

-- Lesson 3
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'The Client Onboarding Process',
  'A professional onboarding process is what separates a ₱15,000 chatbot builder from a ₱50,000 automation consultant. When a prospect says "yes," the next 48 hours determine whether they become a happy, long-term client or a headache. According to a 2025 ClientSuccess report, 23% of client churn happens in the first 30 days due to poor onboarding. In the Philippine business culture, where personal relationships drive business decisions, a smooth onboarding experience builds the trust that leads to referrals and long-term retention. Your onboarding workflow: Step 1 — Discovery Call (30 minutes). Use Calendly or Google Calendar for scheduling. Agenda: understand their business (products, customers, volume), identify pain points (what frustrates them most about customer service), discuss goals (reduce response time, capture more leads, handle after-hours inquiries), assess technical readiness (do they have a Facebook Page, website, Instagram business account?), and set expectations (timeline, deliverables, what you need from them). Use a standardized discovery call script so you never forget key questions. Record the call (with permission) for reference. Step 2 — Audit and Proposal (24 hours after call). Analyze their current customer service: message their business as a mystery shopper, review their Facebook Page response rate (visible publicly), note their current automation (if any). Create a customized proposal using your template: Executive summary of their situation, recommended package, timeline (typically 1-2 weeks for setup), investment (your package price), and expected ROI (based on their volume and current costs). Filipino business tip: include a personal note referencing something specific from the discovery call — Filipinos value personal connection in business relationships. Step 3 — Agreement and Payment. Use a simple service agreement template (Google Doc or PDF): scope of work, deliverables, timeline, payment terms (50% upfront, 50% on delivery — non-negotiable), revision policy (1 round of major revisions, minor tweaks unlimited during setup), and maintenance terms (monthly fee, what is included, cancellation policy). Payment via GCash (instant, preferred by most Filipino business owners), Maya, bank transfer, or PayPal for international clients. Never start work before receiving the upfront payment — this is a professional boundary that protects both parties. Step 4 — Information Gathering (Days 1-3). Send a comprehensive intake form (Google Form): business name, tagline, and brand voice description. Product or service catalog (they can share a Shopee link, menu PDF, or price list). Common customer questions (ask them to forward their 20 most recent customer messages). Operating hours and response time expectations. Team member names for human handoff. Social media credentials (Facebook Page admin access, Instagram login). Special policies (return policy, delivery areas, payment methods accepted). Logo, brand colors, and any existing brand guidelines. Step 5 — Build, Test, Launch (Days 4-14). Build the chatbot based on their specifications. Internal testing (you test every flow). Client testing (they test and provide feedback). Revisions based on feedback. Soft launch (live but monitored closely for 3 days). Full launch with optimization monitoring for the first 2 weeks.',
  'Create your complete onboarding system: (1) Write a discovery call script with 15-20 questions organized by category: business overview, customer service pain points, goals, and technical readiness. Save as a Google Doc you can reference during calls. (2) Create a proposal template in Canva — professional design with sections for situation analysis, recommended solution, timeline, investment, and expected ROI. Leave placeholders for customization. (3) Draft a service agreement template — 2 pages maximum, covering scope, deliverables, timeline, payment, revisions, and maintenance. Have a legally-minded friend review it or use a template from Philippine freelancer legal resources. (4) Build a comprehensive client intake form in Google Forms with at least 20 questions covering everything you need to build their chatbot. Test the form yourself — is it clear? Does it take less than 15 minutes to complete? (5) Create an onboarding email sequence (4 emails): welcome and thank you, intake form request, progress update (Day 7), and launch confirmation. Draft all 4 emails ready to send.',
  'How does having a structured onboarding process change the way you feel about taking on clients? Which step of the process do you think matters most for building client trust? What would happen if you skipped the discovery call and went straight to building — how might that create problems later?',
  3
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Selling Automation Services';

-- Lesson 4
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Case Study: Building a Complete System',
  'Theory is important, but nothing teaches like walking through a real project end-to-end. This lesson follows a complete chatbot automation project for a fictional (but realistic) Philippine business — Bloom Skincare PH, an online beauty brand selling through Shopee, their own Shopify website, and Facebook Page. Their situation mirrors thousands of real Filipino e-commerce businesses. Client Brief: Bloom Skincare PH sells 45 skincare products. They receive 80-120 customer messages per day across Messenger (60%), Instagram DMs (25%), and website chat (15%). Current team: 1 full-time customer service agent (₱18,000/month) and the owner handles overflow. Response time averages 2-4 hours during business hours, no after-hours coverage. Common inquiries: product recommendations for skin types (30%), order status (25%), ingredient questions (20%), returns and exchanges (10%), and other (15%). Monthly revenue: ₱450,000. Estimated lost sales from slow responses: ₱40,000-₱60,000/month. Project Scope (Professional Automation Package — ₱45,000 setup + ₱10,000/month): Build Phase Week 1 — Knowledge base creation. Compile all 45 products with details (ingredients, skin type compatibility, price, size, usage instructions). Document all policies (return within 7 days for unopened products, shipping via J&T and LBC, COD available for orders over ₱500, GCash and Maya accepted). Write 30 FAQ answers covering the most common questions. Create the AI system prompt with Bloom brand voice: "friendly, knowledgeable, like a trusted ate giving skincare advice." Build Phase Week 2 — Chatbot construction. ManyChat for Messenger and Instagram: welcome flow with skin type quiz (oily, dry, combination, sensitive) that leads to personalized product recommendations. Order tracking flow connected to their Shopify order data via Google Sheets. FAQ automation with 15 keyword triggers covering English and Filipino variations. Post-purchase follow-up sequence (Day 1: order confirmation, Day 3: shipping update, Day 7: "How is your skin doing?" check-in with review request). Tidio for website: AI-powered chat with full knowledge base integration. Proactive engagement trigger: visitors on product pages for 2+ minutes get "Need help choosing? I know our products inside out." Lead capture for visitors who browse but do not purchase — email collection with 10% discount offer. Integration: Claude API via Zapier for handling complex product and ingredient questions that go beyond keyword matching. Build Phase Week 3 — Testing and launch. 3 days of internal testing covering every flow path. 2 days of client testing with feedback. 2 days of soft launch with 100% response monitoring. Go live with Week 1 optimization period. Results After 30 Days: automated resolution rate 72%, average response time from 3 hours to 8 seconds, CSAT score 84% (up from estimated 60%), human agent workload reduced by 65% (agent now handles only complex issues and VIP customers), 340 email leads captured via website chatbot, estimated revenue impact: ₱35,000 in recovered sales from faster responses and after-hours coverage. The client ROI: ₱45,000 setup fee pays for itself in 6 weeks of recovered revenue. Monthly ₱10,000 maintenance is offset by reduced need for a second customer service hire they were planning (₱18,000/month savings).',
  'Build the Bloom Skincare PH chatbot as a portfolio project: (1) Create the complete knowledge base document — invent 10 products with realistic details (names, ingredients, prices in pesos, skin type recommendations, sizes). Write 20 FAQ answers and the full policy document. This should be 3,000+ words. (2) Build the ManyChat chatbot with: skin type quiz flow leading to product recommendations, order tracking flow (simulated — use static responses), FAQ automation with 10+ keyword triggers, and post-purchase 3-message sequence. (3) Set up the AI integration: connect Claude via Zapier to handle open-ended product questions using your knowledge base and system prompt. Test with 10 different ingredient and product questions. (4) Build the Tidio website chat: install on a test Shopify or WordPress site, configure AI responses with your knowledge base, and set up the proactive engagement trigger. (5) Document everything: create a case study PDF with client brief, solution overview, build process, results (projected), and screenshots of every chatbot flow. This case study becomes the centerpiece of your portfolio.',
  'How does building a complete end-to-end project feel different from building individual components in isolation? What was the most time-consuming part of the project — knowledge base creation, chatbot building, AI integration, or testing? How would you present this case study to a potential client to demonstrate your capabilities?',
  4
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Selling Automation Services';

-- Lesson 5
insert into public.lessons (module_id, title, description, action_step, reflection_prompt, "order")
select m.id,
  'Building Your Automation Business',
  'You have built the skills, created the tools, and completed a full portfolio project. Now it is time to build a sustainable business that grows beyond your individual capacity. The automation services market in the Philippines is projected to reach ₱15 billion by 2027, growing at 40% annually according to a 2025 International Data Corporation Southeast Asia report. You are entering this market at the perfect time — early enough to establish authority, late enough that demand is proven. The path from freelancer to business: Phase 1 (Months 1-3): Solo Operator. Target: 3 clients, ₱30,000-₱50,000/month. Focus entirely on delivery excellence. Every client should become a case study and referral source. Reinvest 20% of revenue into tools and learning. Build your systems: intake forms, SOPs, templates, and reporting processes. Phase 2 (Months 4-6): Systemized Solo. Target: 5-7 clients, ₱60,000-₱90,000/month. Your systems allow you to serve more clients in less time. Begin hiring process for your first assistant (₱10,000-₱15,000/month part-time). Assistant handles: chatbot monitoring, basic flow updates, data entry for reports, and client communication routing. You handle: sales, strategy, complex builds, AI integration, and client relationships. Phase 3 (Months 7-12): Small Team. Target: 8-12 clients, ₱100,000-₱160,000/month. Team: you + 1 full-time bot builder + 1 part-time account manager. Revenue split: 60% delivery costs and salaries, 40% profit. Begin white-labeling: other agencies and freelancers resell your chatbot services under their brand. You build, they sell and manage the client relationship. White-label pricing: 50-60% of retail (you charge them ₱20,000 for a bot they sell for ₱40,000). This adds volume without adding direct client management. Phase 4 (Year 2+): Automation Agency. Target: 20+ clients, ₱200,000-₱300,000/month. Team: you + 2-3 bot builders + 1 account manager + 1 sales person. Multiple revenue streams: project builds, monthly retainers, white-label services, training workshops, and digital products (chatbot templates sold on Gumroad or your website for ₱1,500-₱5,000 each). At this phase, you are managing a business, not building chatbots. Your role: strategy, sales, team development, and client relationships. Recurring revenue is the foundation: a business with 15 clients on ₱10,000/month retainers has ₱150,000 in predictable monthly income before any new project revenue. This stability allows you to invest in growth, hire confidently, and weather slow months. The goal: 70%+ of revenue from retainers. Financial management: register properly with BIR, set aside 8-12% for taxes (graduated income tax rates in the Philippines), maintain 3 months of operating expenses in reserve, and separate business and personal finances using a dedicated business bank account. At ₱150,000+/month, consult an accountant — the investment of ₱3,000-₱5,000/month saves you from tax issues and enables smarter financial decisions. The mindset shift: you are no longer selling chatbots. You are selling business growth powered by automation. Your clients do not care about ManyChat features or API integrations. They care about more sales, happier customers, lower costs, and peace of mind. Speak their language, deliver on your promises, and build relationships. In the Philippines, where business is deeply personal, your reputation is your most valuable asset. Guard it by over-delivering on every project.',
  'Build your 12-month business plan: (1) Create a financial model in Google Sheets: month-by-month projections for revenue (retainers + projects), expenses (tools, team, taxes), and profit. Model 3 scenarios: conservative (3 new clients/quarter), moderate (5 new clients/quarter), and aggressive (8 new clients/quarter). (2) Write your Phase 1 action plan for the first 90 days: specific client acquisition targets, tools to set up, templates to create, and weekly time allocation (sales: 10 hours, delivery: 20 hours, learning: 5 hours, admin: 5 hours). (3) Create one digital product — a chatbot template package or a "How to Set Up a Messenger Chatbot" mini-guide — and list it on Gumroad at ₱1,500. This is your first passive income stream. (4) Register your business with DTI if you have not already (₱200-₱500, 15 minutes online). Set up a business GCash or Maya account for receiving client payments. (5) Write your 12-month vision statement: where is your business, how many clients, what is your monthly income, who is on your team, and how has your life changed? Share it with one person you trust — accountability accelerates achievement.',
  'Looking back at this entire AI Customer Service Automation track — from understanding why businesses need chatbots to planning a ₱200,000+/month automation agency — what has changed about how you see your career options? What is the single most valuable skill or insight you gained across these 25 lessons? If you follow through on your 12-month plan, how will it transform not just your income, but your confidence, your daily life, and your ability to help others in the Philippines achieve financial independence?',
  5
from public.modules m where m.title = 'Selling Automation Services';
